[[File:Ptuj_-_Orfejev_spomenik_3.jpg|thumb|The Orpheus monument was originally a grave marker of Marcus Valerius Verus, the mayor of Poetovio in the 2nd century AD]] The '''Orpheus Monument''' ({{lang-sl|Orfejev spomenik}}) is a [[Roman Empire|Roman]] monument in [[Ptuj]], [[Slovenia]], an almost {{convert|5|m}} high and about {{convert|1.8|m}} wide [[stele]], carved of white [[Pohorje marble]]. It is located at [[Slovene Square, Ptuj|Slovene Square]] ({{lang-sl|Slovenski trg}}), the town's central square, in front of the [[Town Tower, Ptuj|Town Tower]]. It is the oldest public monument preserved in its original location in Slovenia,<ref name="SI">[http://www.slovenia.info/?arhitekturne_znamenitosti=6532 Slovenia info]</ref> the largest discovered monument from the Roman province of the [[Pannonia Superior]],<ref name="PMP">{{cite web |url=http://www.pok-muzej-ptuj.si/index/the_povoden_museum_and_the_orpheus_monument/lang/en/ |title=The Povoden Museum and the Orpheus Monument |publisher=Ptuj Ormož Regional Museum |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref> and the symbol of Ptuj.<ref name="RKD7754" />
The monolith was originally a [[Headstone|grave marker]], erected in the 2nd century AD to honor the memory of Marcus Valerius Verus, the [[duumviri|duumvir]] (mayor) of [[Roman Empire|Roman]] [[Poetovio]].<ref name="RKD7754" /> In the [[Middle Ages]], it was used as a [[pillory]].<ref name="RKD7754" /> Criminals were tied to the iron rings attached to its lower part.<ref name="PMP" /> Since March 2008, it has the status of a national cultural monument.<ref name="RKD7754">{{cite web |url=http://giskd2s.situla.org/rkd/Opis.asp?Esd=7754 |title=7754: Ptuj - Orfejev spomenik |trans-title=7754: Ptuj – Orpheus Monument |work=Register nepremične kulturne dediščine [Registry of Immovable Cultural Heritage] |publisher=Ministrstvo za kulturo Republike Slovenije |language=Slovenian |accessdate=30 May 2012}}</ref>
The central relief illustrates scenes from the myth of [[Orpheus]], who plays the lyre while mourning his lost love [[Eurydice]]. Other reliefs depict the Greek-Egyptian god [[Serapis]], who symbolizes the hope of resurrection. The corners each contain a prone lion gnawing on a ram's head. Beneath this, a relief in the tympanum depicts the Moon goddess [[Selene]], leaning over her dead lover [[Endymion (mythology)|Endymion]]. All the reliefs and inscriptions are badly eroded.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.si/books?id=ehVXAAAAYAAJ |title=Ptujski arheološki zbornik: ob 100-letnici muzeja in Muzejskega društva |language=Slovenian, English|trans-title=Ptuj Collection of Archeological Papers: On the 100th Anniversary of the Museum and the Museum Society |publisher=Regional Museum of Ptuj |year=1993 |editor-first=Brane |editor-last=Lamut |id={{COBISS|ID=35226880}}}}</ref>
