{{Infobox book | name = William's Doll | image = William's Doll (1972 book).jpg | image_size = | caption = | alt = | author = [[Charlotte Zolotow]] | title_orig = | translator = | illustrator = [[William Pène du Bois]] | cover_artist = | country = | language = | series = | subject = | genre = [[Picture book]] | publisher = Harper & Row | pub_date = 1972 | english_pub_date = | media_type = | pages = 30 pp | awards = | isbn = 978-0-06-443067-8 | oclc = 347798 | dewey = | congress = | preceded_by = | followed_by = | wikisource = }}
'''''William's Doll''''' is a 1972 children's [[picture book]] by [[Charlotte Zolotow]] about a boy who wants a [[doll]] even though dolls typically are considered [[gender role|a toy only for girls]]. His father, uncomfortable with William's request, tries giving William toys the father considers more [[gender]]-appropriate, such as a [[basketball]] and a [[train set]]; while William enjoys these toys, he continues to ask for a doll. Eventually, the boy's grandmother fulfills the request, explaining to the father that William will use the doll to practice being a good father.
Zolotow has explained that although she is a [[feminist]] and appreciates that many feminists enjoyed the book's message, her inspiration was more from personal observations about her husband's early attempts to bond with the couple's son, Stephen, and about how men of the time period missed out on some of the pleasures of being closely involved with their children's development. She observed, for example, that by always exiting the room during diaper changes, her husband missed their son's first smile.<ref name="zolotowcom">[http://www.charlottezolotow.com/willilams_doll.htm Charlotte Zolotow on the origins of ''William's Doll''], charlottezolotow.com (retrieved June 1, 2007)</ref>
The book often is used in the United States for lessons on gender roles, [[stereotype]]s, or general anti-[[bias]] education. For example, the journal article "'William's Doll' Revisited" was on a study comparing reactions of [[fourth grade|fourth-grade]] students in 1975 and in 2000.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Greever |first=Ellen A. |last2=Austin |first2=Patricia |last3=Welhousen |first3=Karyn |date=March 2000 |title='William's Doll' Revisited |journal=Language Arts |volume=77 |issue=4 |pages=324–30 |format=PDF |issn=0360-9170 |accessdate=July 31, 2012 |url=http://www.csun.edu/~bashforth/305_PDF/305_ME2/305_Language&Gender/WilliamsDollRevisitedAcross20Years_LA2000.pdf |laysource=[[Education Resources Information Center]] |laysummary=http://www.eric.ed.gov/ERICWebPortal/search/detailmini.jsp?_nfpb=true&_&ERICExtSearch_SearchValue_0=EJ603237&ERICExtSearch_SearchType_0=no&accno=EJ603237 |laydate= |quote= |ref= |separator= |postscript= }}</ref>
==Adaptations== A song based on the story, with music by [[Mary Rodgers]] and lyrics by [[Sheldon Harnick]], was included in the best-selling ''[[Free to Be... You and Me]]'' children's [[album]] and [[songbook]] in 1972, where it was sung by [[Alan Alda]] and [[Marlo Thomas]]. (This same song was sung by [[B. D. Wong]] at the [[Ms. Foundation]]'s 15th Annual Gloria Awards ceremony in 2003, where Marlo Thomas and former Ms. Foundation president Letty Cottin Pogrebin received the Creative Philanthropy Award for the album's creation.<ref name="mcsr">[http://www.mencanstoprape.org/info-url2699/info-url_show.htm?doc_id=170569 "Yoko Ono Presents Award"] (undated article, retrieved June 1, 2007)</ref>)
When ''Free to Be... You and Me'' became a television special in [[1974 in television|1974]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] asked producer Marlo Thomas to make two changes to the material, one of which involved the Zolotow story: {{Cquote|They wanted ''William's Doll'' cut, because it would turn every boy in the world into a homosexual &mdash; which isn't such a bad idea. And the other issue was "Parents Are People." Harry Belafonte sang the man part and I sang the female part, and we were walking down Fifth Avenue pushing baby buggies and ABC said it wouldn't play in the South. It looked like we were married. ... Thankfully, 'That Girl' was a hit on ABC at the time, so I had a little clout. Both things stayed in.|20px|20px|Marlo Thomas|''Forward'', May 28, 2004<ref name="jccny">Majorie Ingall, [http://www.jccmanhattan.org/category.aspx?catid=1795 "The East Village Mamele; Why 'Free to Be...' Still Kicks Butt,"] ''Forward'', [[Jewish Community Center|JCC Manhattan]], May 28, 2004</ref>}}
''William's Doll'' also became a 14-minute film in [[1981 in film|1981]].<ref name="zolotowcom"/> The 1981 film starred Craig Salles as William and was shot in Graceada Park in Modesto, California. In [[2010 in film|2010]], the producers of [[RiffTrax]], formerly [[Mystery Science Theater 3000]], released ''William's Doll''.<ref>[http://www.rifftrax.com/shorts/williams-doll William's Doll]. rifftrax.com</ref> This was their "riff" of the aforementioned short.
